The paper deals with complexity theory and algorithm design, specifically in the context of shaving logarithmic factors from the running time of fundamental combinatorial problems. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-category. Additionally, the paper focuses on problems in data structures (such as LCS and regular expression pattern matching), computational geometry (such as the Fr\'echet distance problem), and discrete mathematics (such as Formula-SAT), which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.DS, cs.CG, and cs.DM sub-categories. Finally, the paper may also be relevant to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category, as shaving logarithmic factors is a common technique in the design of efficient machine learning algorithms.
